e from Virginia, brought through New York in 1852 by their owners, Juliet and Jonathan Lemmon. The Eight were in court seeking, legally, to become people—to change their status under law from objects into human beings. The Eight encountered Louis Napoleon, the son of a slave, an abolitionist activist, and a "conductor" of the Underground Railroad, who took enormous risks to help others. He was part of an anti-slavery movement in which African-Americans played an integral role in the fight for freedom. The case was part of the broader judicial landscape at the time: If a law was morally repugnant but enshrined in the Constitution, what was the duty of the judge? Should there be, as some people advocated, a "higher law" that transcends the written law? These questions were at the heart of the Lemmon case. They were difficult and important ones in the 1850s—and, more than a century and a half later, we must still grapple with them today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHabeas corpusxNew York (State)xHistoryy19th centuryxCases2DLC. 0aHabeas corpusxNew York (State)xHistoryy19th centuryxCases. 0aLemmon, Jonathan, active 1852-1860xTrials, litigation, etc2DLC. 0aLemmon, Jonathan, active 1852-1860xTrials, litigation, etc. 0aSlaveryxLaw and legislationxNew York (State)xHistoryy19th centuryxCases2DLC. 0aSlaveryxLaw and legislationxNew York (State)xHistoryy19th centuryxCases. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aGeneral Interest : General Interest. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPolitics and Law : Legal Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Middle Atlantic (DC, DE, MD, NJ, NY, PA).2bisacsh1 aLohier Jr., Judge Raymond J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Pre